00:00:03.570 --> 00:00:05.560
Let's look at a
typical application

00:00:05.560 --> 00:00:08.570
of Newton's second law
for a system of objects.

00:00:08.570 --> 00:00:13.000
So what I want to consider is
a system of pulleys and masses.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.670
So I'll have a fixed
surface here, a ceiling.

00:00:17.670 --> 00:00:20.770
And from the ceiling,
we'll hang a pulley, which

00:00:20.770 --> 00:00:23.970
I'm going to call pulley
A. And this pulley will

00:00:23.970 --> 00:00:28.350
have a rope attached to
it, wrapped around it.

00:00:28.350 --> 00:00:31.090
And here we have object 1.

00:00:31.090 --> 00:00:34.220
And the rope goes
around the pulley.

00:00:34.220 --> 00:00:40.880
And now it's going to go
around another pulley B

00:00:40.880 --> 00:00:44.550
and fixed to the ceiling.

00:00:44.550 --> 00:00:46.880
So that's fixed.

00:00:46.880 --> 00:00:52.200
And hanging from pulley
B is another mass 2.

00:00:52.200 --> 00:00:55.060
And our goal in applying
Newton's second law

00:00:55.060 --> 00:00:59.180
is to find the accelerations
of objects 1 and 2.

00:00:59.180 --> 00:01:01.390
Now, how do we approach this?

00:01:01.390 --> 00:01:03.260
Well, the first
thing we have to do

00:01:03.260 --> 00:01:07.000
is decide if we're going to
apply Newton's second law, what

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:09.490
is the system that
we'll apply it to?

00:01:09.490 --> 00:01:12.090
And there's many different
ways to choose a system.

00:01:12.090 --> 00:01:14.240
When we look at
this problem, we'll

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:16.850
have several different systems.

00:01:16.850 --> 00:01:19.710
So let's consider the ones
that we're going to look at.

00:01:19.710 --> 00:01:21.360
And the first one
is very simple.

00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:24.640
It will be block 1.

00:01:24.640 --> 00:01:26.440
And the second system
that we look at,

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:31.470
we'll call that AB is pulley A.

00:01:31.470 --> 00:01:33.860
Now that brings us to
an interesting question

00:01:33.860 --> 00:01:38.810
about pulley B and block 2,
because we could separately

00:01:38.810 --> 00:01:43.210
look at pulley B, and we could
separately consider block 2,

00:01:43.210 --> 00:01:44.979
or we consider them together.

00:01:44.979 --> 00:01:52.840
And I want to first
consider separately pulley B

00:01:52.840 --> 00:01:55.680
and block 2.

00:01:55.680 --> 00:02:00.480
Now in some ways when you're
looking at a compound system,

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:02.600
and it has four
objects, it makes sense

00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:05.720
to apply Newton's second law
to each object separately.

00:02:05.720 --> 00:02:08.538
But we'll pay careful
attention to the fact

00:02:08.538 --> 00:02:11.760
that object 2 is
connected to pulley B.

00:02:11.760 --> 00:02:14.030
And eventually,
we'll see that we

00:02:14.030 --> 00:02:16.560
can combine these two things.

00:02:16.560 --> 00:02:19.390
So the next step is
once we have identified

00:02:19.390 --> 00:02:22.430
our object is to draw a free
body force diagrams for each

00:02:22.430 --> 00:02:23.530
of the objects.

00:02:23.530 --> 00:02:27.760
So in order to do that,
let's start with object 1.

00:02:27.760 --> 00:02:32.620
And we want to consider
the forces on object 1.

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:34.710
Now that brings us
to our first issue

00:02:34.710 --> 00:02:38.490
about what types of assumptions
we're making in our system.

00:02:38.490 --> 00:02:40.380
For instance, we
have a rope that's

00:02:40.380 --> 00:02:41.730
wrapped around this pulley.

00:02:41.730 --> 00:02:45.610
And we have two pulleys that
in principle could be rotating.

00:02:45.610 --> 00:02:48.920
But what we'd like to do to
simplify our analysis-- so

00:02:48.920 --> 00:02:53.070
let's keep track of
some assumptions here.

00:02:53.070 --> 00:03:01.615
Our first assumption will be
that the mass, MP, of pulley A

00:03:01.615 --> 00:03:05.740
and the mass of pulley B
are approximately zero.

00:03:05.740 --> 00:03:08.300
Now the reason for
that is that we're not

00:03:08.300 --> 00:03:09.750
going to consider
any of the fact

00:03:09.750 --> 00:03:13.410
that these objects have to be
put into rotational motion.

00:03:13.410 --> 00:03:16.270
Later on in the course, we'll
see that this will give us

00:03:16.270 --> 00:03:19.150
a more complicated analysis.

00:03:19.150 --> 00:03:22.420
We're also going to assume
that our rope is not slipping.

00:03:22.420 --> 00:03:28.650
So the rope is actually is
just slipping on the pulleys.

00:03:28.650 --> 00:03:31.050
So what that means is
it's just the rope is

00:03:31.050 --> 00:03:34.320
sliding as the objects move.

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:37.910
Now again, what this
is going to imply

00:03:37.910 --> 00:03:41.430
is that the tension in
the rope-- this rope

00:03:41.430 --> 00:03:43.329
is also slipping.

00:03:43.329 --> 00:03:48.000
And the rope is
massless as well.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:49.380
It's very light rope.

00:03:49.380 --> 00:03:50.970
And all of these
assumptions we've

00:03:50.970 --> 00:03:54.140
seen when we analyze
ropes tell us

00:03:54.140 --> 00:03:59.850
that the tension T is
uniform in the rope.

00:03:59.850 --> 00:04:02.000
So that's our first assumption.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.280
And we need to think
about this before we even

00:04:04.280 --> 00:04:06.490
begin to think about the
forces on the object.

00:04:06.490 --> 00:04:08.480
And now we can draw our forces.

00:04:08.480 --> 00:04:09.690
What do we have?

00:04:09.690 --> 00:04:12.370
We have the gravitational
force on object 1.

00:04:12.370 --> 00:04:16.519
And now we can identify the
tension pulling in the string,

00:04:16.519 --> 00:04:18.579
pulling object 1 up.

00:04:18.579 --> 00:04:22.430
Now for every time we
introduce a free body diagram,

00:04:22.430 --> 00:04:25.040
recall that we
have to choose what

00:04:25.040 --> 00:04:27.550
we mean by positive directions.

00:04:27.550 --> 00:04:31.800
And in this case, I'm going to
pick a unit vector down, j hat

00:04:31.800 --> 00:04:33.310
1 down.

